  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 대의 : '
    value: 《화엄경(華嚴經)》을 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 문수(文殊)의……법문도 : '
    value: 문수(文殊)보살은 지혜를 위주로 한 보살이요, 보현(普賢)은 행실과 원력[行願]을 위주로 한 보살인데 모두 《화엄경》에 상세히 있다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 밀인(密印) : '
    value: 선종(禪宗)에서 이심전심(以心傳心)하는 것을 조인(祖印)이니 밀인(密印)이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 혹은 운봉산……했다 : '
    value: 옛날 인도(印度)에서는 여름철에 더위가 심하므로 불법을 수행하는 사람들이 여름 석 달에는 출입하지 아니하고 한 곳에 모여 공부한다. 이것을 하안거(夏安居)라 하여 중국과 우리나라에서도 그렇게 하여 왔다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 근기(根機)는……적시어 : '
    value: 불경에 “온갖 초목에 한 비가 적시면 초목들이 각기 제대로 혜택을 받는다.” 하였는데, 이것은, 부처의 가르침은 한 가지이나 중생이 근기에 따라서 각기 이익을 얻는다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 부모를……의심하듯 : '
    value: 《예기(禮記)》에 부모의 상(喪)을 장사 지낼 때에, “상여를 메고 가는 것은 생각하는 듯하고, 돌아올 때에는 의심하는 듯하다.” 하였으니, 차마 떠나 보낼 수 없어 멈칫거리고 그리워한다는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 금단(金壇)과 옥급(玉笈) : '
    value: 금단(金壇)은 신선이 사는 곳이요, 옥급(玉笈)은 도교(道敎)의 비서(秘書)를 감춘 상자이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 장자방(張子房)이……받은 것 : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 장량(張良)의 자(字)가 자방인데, 황석공(黃石公)이란 신인(神人)에게 소서(素書)라는 글을 얻어서 그것을 써 한 고조(漢高祖)의 창업을 보좌하였다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 보지 대사(寶誌大師)가……예언함 : '
    value: 육조(六祖)시대에 보지(寶誌)라는 신승(神僧)이 있어 술법이 많고 예언을 많이 하였는데 꼭꼭 맞았다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 일행(一行)……정통한 것 : '
    value: 일행(一行)은 당나라 중으로 술수에 통하였는데 특히 천문학에 능하고 예언도 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 일념(一念)이 천겁(千劫) : '
    value: 일념(一念)은 가장 짧은 시각을 말하고 천겁은 영원한 시간을 말하는데, 불법을 깨달으면 시간을 초월한다는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 交 : '
    value: 文
  - key: '[주-D002] 自 : '
    value: 目
  - key: '[주-D003] 跌 : '
    value: 趺
  - key: '[주-D004] ▣ : '
    value: 雖
english:
  title: Stele Inscription for National Preceptor Seonggak at Okryong Temple on Baekgye Mountain
  author: Choe Yu-cheong
  language: eng
  text: "In the fourth year of the sovereign's reign, the tenth month, on the day of sinyu, the ruler commanded his servant thus: \"Consider how the National Preceptor Seonggak's noble virtue flourished in our realm, his accomplishments ran deepest of all. Our ancestors bestowed upon him honor upon honor, reaching the zenith of esteem. Yet his deeds remain unwritten until this day, and I am ashamed. My father, the late king, already commanded you to compose this account. Attend to it with reverence.\" \n\nHearing this command, I trembled with awe, withdrew to my chamber, and gathered the detailed facts of his life, which I now set forth in order.\n\nThe Master was known as Doseon. His lay surname was Kim, and he came from Yeongam in Silla. His ancestral line and forbears are lost to history, though some say he descended from a collateral branch of King Taejong. His mother, Lady Kang, dreamed that a person gave her a luminous pearl and bade her swallow it. Conceiving thereafter, she abstained from pungent foods for the entire month, devoting herself only to scripture-reading and Buddha-invocation.\n\nFrom infancy, he was extraordinary among children. Even at play or in tears, his spirit showed reverence for the Buddha's teaching. His parents perceived he would become a vessel of the dharma and resolved to let him enter monastic life. At fifteen, sharp and mature beyond his years, skilled in all arts, he shaved his head and studied the great sutras at Hwaeom Temple. Before a year had passed, he grasped the profound meanings—the subtle wisdom of Manjushri and the mysterious gate of Samantabhadra—all entering without obstruction. His hundreds of fellow students marveled, calling him divinely gifted.\n\nIn the eighth year of King Munseong's reign, at twenty, he suddenly thought: \"A great man should depart from learning and dwell in stillness. Why remain bound to mere words?\" At that time, the great Master Hyecheol received the seal of mind-to-mind transmission from Master Jijang and opened a teaching seat at Dongrishan. Many sought him out. Our Master approached the Chan gate humbly, requesting discipleship. The great Master, seeing his brilliance, received him with utmost sincerity, transmitting what cannot be spoken, what cannot be grasped—the wordless word, the lawless law—until the student awakened in sudden clarity.\n\nAt twenty-three, he received the full precepts at Cheondosa. Having penetrated the ultimate meaning, he wandered without fixed abode, treading through mist and streams, seeking hidden places and rare vistas, never resting. Now he would pierce a mountain cavern to meditate on a cloudy peak; now he would build a grass hut before great rocks to spend the summer retreat. His fame spread throughout the realm, revered across the seas. Wondrous traces attended his practice, yet I record only the essential.\n\nAt Baekgye Mountain in Heeyang County stood an ancient temple called Okryong. When the Master passed that way, he loved its secluded beauty, restored the halls, and resolved to end his days there. He sat in silent meditation for thirty-five years, his tongue forgotten. From all quarters, students flocked like clouds, their shadows following his shade—hundreds of disciples bearing his robes and staff. Though their capacities differed vastly, a single rain wetted them all equally. They came as empty vessels, receiving through direct pointing, and departed filled with understanding.\n\nKing Heongang heard of his lofty virtue and sent an envoy to invite him. Upon their first meeting, the king rejoiced and urged him to remain in the palace, where the Master frequently opened the royal mind with profound discourse. Yet he soon grew weary of the capital and humbly requested return to his temple.\n\nOne day he suddenly called his disciples: \"I shall depart now. That which comes through conditions departs when conditions end—this is the natural way. Why grieve?\" With these words, he crossed his legs in meditation posture and entered final repose. This was the tenth day of the third month in the first year of Tang's Guanghua era—he was seventy-two. The four assemblies wept as if mourning parents, reluctant to let him go. They moved his seated form and erected a stupa at the northern ridge of the temple, honoring his final wish.\n\nKing Hyogong heard and sorrowed deeply. He bestowed the posthumous name \"Enlightened Empty Master\" and named the stupa \"Tower of Verified Sagely Radiance.\" His disciples, headed by Hongjeok, fearing his illustrious deeds would fade, tearfully presented a petition requesting that his life be recorded. The king commanded Scholar Park Inbeom to compose a stele inscription, though it was never carved.\n\nBefore establishing Okryong Temple, the Master dwelt in a hermitage at Guryeong on Jirisan. One day a strange person appeared before him and spoke: \"I have dwelt hidden from the world nearly three hundred years. Though I possess small arts, I wish to offer them to you. If you do not disdain them as base techniques, I shall bestow them upon you at the shores of the southern sea. This too is the bodhisattva's method of saving the world and liberating beings.\" Then he vanished.\n\nThe Master, astonished, journeyed to that shore and indeed encountered the person, who gathered sand into mountains and streams, showing him their auspicious and inauspicious configurations. When the Master turned around, the stranger had disappeared. That place, now in Gulle County, is called Sand-Map Village by the people.\n\nFrom that time forth, the Master gained clear insight and devoted himself to studying the methods of yin-yang and the five phases. Even the deepest secrets of immortal texts and Daoist treasures were imprinted upon his heart.\n\nAs Silla's governance declined and signs of ruin appeared, the Master foreknew that a sage would arise to receive the Mandate. He often journeyed to Songak County. At that time our Grandfather, the Founder's father, was building a residence there. When the Master passed his gate, he observed: \"A king will emerge from this place, yet the builder does not understand.\" A maidservant overheard and reported it to the Founder's father, who hastily received him and sought his counsel. The Master advised him to reconstruct the site. He then declared: \"Two years hence, you shall father a noble son.\" The Master composed a sealed scroll and presented it, saying: \"This writing is for your future son, yet give it to him only when he reaches manhood.\"\n\nThat year, King Heongang ascended Silla's throne—the second year of Tang's Qianfu era. Four years later, our Great Progenitor was indeed born at that very house. When he reached manhood and received the scroll, he perceived that Heaven's mandate rested upon him. He then swept away brigands and usurpers, establishing his realm. How could the sage-king have harbored worldly ambition? Rather, through his divine virtue, chaos was cleared, the path was rectified, and the people were elevated to tranquility. His great achievements and beneficent virtue have transmitted endlessly.\n\nThough Heaven aids those of virtue and people revere the humane ruler, the establishment of this auspicious age, determined through heaven's secret reckoning, originated entirely from our Master. Behold the magnitude of his merit and brilliance! Worthy indeed of supreme praise and boundless honor. Therefore King Hyonwang granted him the rank of Great Meditation Master, King Sukjo added the title Royal Preceptor, and our late sagely king, in advancing the accumulated honors of his predecessors, finally elevated him to National Preceptor of Foreknowledge, sending an envoy to perform rites at the temple's portrait hall. Now our present sovereign commands his deeds be inscribed to transmit them eternally. Sublime indeed—nothing greater could be added.\n\nI have ventured to reflect: When an empire is about to arise, its numinous force and celestial aura must first move all things. Thus eminent talents and transcendent vision manifest endlessly—some preceding, some following, each fulfilling their function. The Master's relation to the Great Progenitor was truly magnificent. He foreknew before the birth and his efficacy extended beyond his death. This spiritual accord and hidden support surpasses all comprehension.\n\nThe Master's attainment united with the Buddhas and patriarchs; his traces resembled how Zhang Liang received the Book from a divine being, how Master Baozhi uttered prophecies of things unseen, how the monk Yixing penetrated all calculations. His teachings on yin-yang have spread widely and all geographers honor them.\n\nThe Inscription reads:\n\nBuddhas of ages past\nPossess a subtle dharma—\nNot bound by written words,\nNot grasped through meditation.\nWith sudden pointing, the direct indication:\nOne thought spans a thousand eons.\nOur Master alone\nEntered that realm with ease.\n\nLearning that transcends learning,\nEmptiness beyond void—\nHe held the Eye of True Law,\nFour directions opened, six penetrations manifest.\nEven his remaining traces,\nImplanted in technical arts,\nWithout yarrow or divination,\nRevealed the boundless to come.\n\nWhen the old realm trembled\nAnd the new mandate lay hidden,\nHe knew the ending before it ended,\nPerceived the coming before arrival.\nHe composed a scroll,\nOffering it in advance—\nThus the nation's fortune began.\n\nAs surely as establishing Zhou,\nAs clearly as raising Han,\nAs transparent as pointing at one's palm:\nThe sage arose,\nReceiving the mandate,\nAll relying on what emanated from the Master.\n\nThough generations intervened,\nThe deed and the present align.\nHis singular merit and sacred accomplishment\nRemain eternal as mountain and river.\n\nThree hundred years have passed—\nStill his spirit seems present.\nGazing upon his lofty traces,\nWe see them bold against heaven.\nThis stele, carved in the ancient shrine,\nShall proclaim his name for a thousand ages.\nO Mountain Spirit, hear:\nGuard this place without cease."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The seal of mind-to-mind transmission (密印) represents the Chan Buddhist practice of directly conveying enlightenment from master to student without reliance on words or conceptual understanding.
  - key: ''
    value: The Huayan Sutra (華嚴經), which the Master mastered, centers on Manjushri's transcendent wisdom and Samantabhadra's boundless compassionate action.
  - key: ''
    value: The summer retreat (夏安居) is a monastic practice originating in India where monks remain in one place during the intense heat of summer to focus on practice without traveling.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhang Liang (張良), styled Zifang, received the mysterious text *Shuoshu* from the divine immortal Huangshigong, which enabled him to assist the Han emperor in his founding of the dynasty—a parallel to Doseon's guidance of Korea's founding.
  - key: ''
    value: Master Baozhi (寶誌) was a miraculous monk of the Sixth Patriarchal period known for prophecies that invariably came to pass.
  - key: ''
    value: The monk Yixing (一行) of the Tang dynasty mastered astronomy and divination while maintaining his monastic practice, similar to Doseon's synthesis of Buddhist enlightenment and geomantic science.
